---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What's the AS 4505 wind class for a Cranbourne garage door?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most of Cranbourne, Hampton Park, Junction Village and Clyde fall into AS 4505 wind class N2 (33 m/s peak gust) on standard residential blocks. The newer estates on the southern fringe — Botanic Ridge, Clyde North, the more exposed parts of Cranbourne South near the Western Port wetlands — can push to N3 (41 m/s) where the block sits on open ground without windbreak. We size to the actual classification from your engineer's wind report (or the project-builder spec if it's a new build) rather than defaulting to a single number. N2-rated doors are stocked; N3 is a 7–10 day lead time on the heavier-gauge panel." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Why is sectional usually better than roller on a wind-rated block?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Two reasons. First, sectional panels are 40mm-thick polyurethane-filled with steel inner and outer skins — that's structurally far more rigid than a 0.4mm or 0.5mm roller-door curtain. Second, sectional doors are guided in vertical tracks bolted to the structural frame on both sides, where roller curtains are only held in narrow side-guides. On a high-wind block, a roller curtain can bow inward or escape the guides during a peak gust, where a sectional door stays where it is. For N3-classified Cranbourne blocks we will rarely quote a roller as the primary choice." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Insulation R-value difference between sectional and roller — does it matter on a garage?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "It matters more than you'd think, particularly on a Cranbourne garage that's also a workshop, gym or a kid's hangout. A polyurethane-filled sectional panel comes in at roughly R 2.0 (3.0 on premium variants), where an un-insulated roller curtain is essentially R 0.3. The temperature delta on a 35°C January afternoon is 6–9 degrees cooler inside a sectional-doored garage than a roller-doored one. If the garage adjoins habitable rooms (which is the layout on most Clyde North and Cranbourne East estate homes), the sectional R-value also pulls down the cooling load on the adjacent rooms." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Cost-per-square-metre — what's the 2026 gap?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Roller doors land at $850–$1,400 supplied and fitted on a single-car opening, $1,400–$2,200 on a double. Sectional doors land at $1,650–$2,800 single-car and $2,400–$4,200 double. The cost-per-square-metre averages out to roughly $180/m² on a roller and $310/m² on a sectional. The gap closes once you add motor, insulation and wind-rated upgrades — and over a 20-year window, the sectional's longer panel life (25+ years vs 12–18 for a roller curtain) usually pulls the total cost-of-ownership level or in the sectional's favour." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What about access height — can I fit a 4WD or a trailer through both?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Roller doors give you slightly more headroom on the same opening — typically 80–120mm more, because the curtain rolls up into a much smaller box at the top than the sectional's overhead-tracking rail needs. For a 2.4m-high standard opening, a roller will give you 2.32m of clear drive-through, where a sectional gives 2.20m. On most Cranbourne double-garages that's still plenty for any standard 4WD or boat-on-trailer. The exception is tall caravans or commercial vans, where a roller can be the deciding factor and we may also recommend upgrading the opening height itself rather than fighting the door type." }}
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Sectional vs Roller Garage Doors in Cranbourne — Wind Rating, Insulation and Cost | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Why sectional doors hold up better in higher wind-classified zones around Cranbourne, the AS 4505 wind classification, the panel-thickness difference, the insulation R-value, and the cost-per-square-metre."
  canonical="https://cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au/sectional-vs-roller-cranbourne/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Door type comparison &middot; Cranbourne &amp; City of Casey</span>
      <h1>Sectional vs roller in <span class="accent">Cranbourne</span> &mdash; wind rating, insulation and what it actually costs.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Cranbourne and the southern Casey suburbs sit mostly in AS 4505 wind
        class N2 with patches of N3 across the more exposed Botanic Ridge,
        Clyde North and Cranbourne South blocks. That changes the
        sectional-vs-roller maths in a way the showroom brochures don&rsquo;t
        explain. Free quote with the wind class confirmed against your block.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Send a quote request</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>AS 4505 and what the wind class means for your door.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          AS 4505 is the Australian Standard that classifies garage doors by
          the wind load they must resist without permanently deflecting,
          escaping the guides, or letting daylight through the panel joins.
          The classes run N1 (sheltered, 28 m/s peak gust) through N6
          (extreme, 70 m/s &mdash; cyclone territory). For Cranbourne and the
          surrounding City of Casey suburbs, the practical band is N2 to N3.
        </p>
        <p>
          N2 covers most of Cranbourne CBD, Cranbourne East, Cranbourne West,
          Hampton Park, Junction Village and the older Cranbourne North
          estates &mdash; established streets with mature trees, fence-line
          windbreak, and adjacent house frontage breaking the peak gust load.
          N3 applies on the exposed-paddock blocks on the southern and
          western edges &mdash; particularly newer Botanic Ridge, Clyde North,
          Clyde and the parts of Cranbourne South where the prevailing
          south-westerly off the bay has unbroken fetch onto the block.
        </p>
        <p>
          On an N3 block, a roller curtain with standard 0.4mm steel and
          builder-grade side-guides will bow inward during a peak gust. We
          have seen it &mdash; the curtain pushes into the garage cavity by
          50&ndash;100mm at the centre, occasionally escaping the guide.
          That&rsquo;s not a hypothetical risk; that&rsquo;s a callout we get
          three or four times a year after a serious southerly through the
          Casey corridor.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The panel thickness story.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          A sectional door panel is a sandwich. Steel skin (typically 0.5mm)
          on the outside, polyurethane foam in the middle (35&ndash;45mm
          thick), and another steel skin on the inside. Total panel thickness
          is around 40mm, with internal stiffeners on the wider double-car
          panels. Structurally, this acts like a stressed-skin honeycomb panel
          &mdash; far more rigid than the steel thickness alone would suggest.
        </p>
        <p>
          A roller-door curtain is a single skin of corrugated steel, typically
          0.4mm or 0.5mm, with no insulation and no inner skin. The corrugation
          provides some bending rigidity along the curtain's length, but
          essentially none across its width. On a 5m-wide double-car opening
          that&rsquo;s a long unsupported span when wind loads on it. Solid
          curtain rollers (Steel-Line Smartline, B&amp;D Firmadoor, ATA Premier)
          exist and are wind-rated up to N3 with the heavier 0.6mm gauge plus
          reinforced guides &mdash; we&rsquo;re happy to quote that
          configuration where the access-height advantage of a roller really
          matters.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The cost picture across a 20-year horizon.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Roller, single-car:</strong> $850&ndash;$1,400 fitted. Curtain life 12&ndash;18 years. Insulation R 0.3. Repaint or replace at year 12&ndash;15.</li>
          <li><strong>Roller, double-car:</strong> $1,400&ndash;$2,200 fitted. Same curtain life as single-car. Heavier curtain means earlier guide wear on N3 blocks.</li>
          <li><strong>Sectional, single-car standard:</strong> $1,650&ndash;$2,300 fitted. Panel life 25+ years. Insulation R 2.0. Re-paint not needed &mdash; the Colorbond finish is the topcoat.</li>
          <li><strong>Sectional, single-car premium:</strong> $2,300&ndash;$2,800 fitted. R 3.0 insulation, heavier 0.6mm skin, full N3 wind compliance, designer-finish options.</li>
          <li><strong>Sectional, double-car standard:</strong> $2,400&ndash;$3,200 fitted. Same panel and motor lifecycle as single-car.</li>
          <li><strong>Sectional, double-car premium:</strong> $3,200&ndash;$4,200 fitted. Full N3 rating, R 3.0, Colorbond Matt or woodgrain-finish panel options.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
          The sectional door's longer panel life and built-in insulation
          usually level the total-cost-of-ownership over 20 years, even
          before you factor in the cooling-load benefit on the adjoining
          rooms. On an N3 block specifically &mdash; new Clyde North or
          Botanic Ridge build &mdash; we&rsquo;d only ever recommend a roller
          if access-height clearance is the deciding constraint.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Common questions on sectional vs roller in Cranbourne.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>Can a sectional door be retrofitted into an opening built for a roller?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes, in 90% of cases. The opening height usually accommodates the
          sectional&rsquo;s overhead-tracking rail (you lose 80&ndash;120mm of
          headroom compared to a roller). The width is universal. We&rsquo;ll
          measure the lintel-to-ceiling clearance and the side-room clearance
          for the vertical tracks before quoting; if a low-headroom kit is
          needed it adds about $250 to the install.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Are sectional doors louder to operate than roller doors?</h3>
        <p>
          Slightly &mdash; the panels articulating around the curve at the top
          of the track produce a measurable sound the roller curtain doesn't.
          But on a belt-drive motor with quality nylon rollers, the difference
          is around 3&ndash;5 dB &mdash; not enough to matter in practice.
          What does matter is the motor itself: a chain-drive on either door
          type is noticeably louder than a belt-drive on either door type.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What about salt-air corrosion &mdash; we're not far from Westernport?</h3>
        <p>
          The southern parts of Cranbourne and Cranbourne South are within the
          15km salt-aerosol zone from Westernport Bay. We default to
          Colorbond Coastline-grade finishes (not standard Colorbond) on doors
          in this zone, with stainless-steel hardware on the spring fixings
          and roller pivots. Adds roughly 5% to the door price, doubles the
          surface-finish warranty.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Does the AS 4505 wind class affect my insurance?</h3>
        <p>
          It can &mdash; some insurers want documentation that the door is
          rated to the wind class on the site engineer's report, particularly
          on newer Clyde North and Botanic Ridge contracts. We supply the
          AS 4505 compliance certificate as part of the handover paperwork on
          every new-door install. Existing-door customers wanting documentation
          can request a retrofit compliance inspection at $180.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2>Wind class checked, quote in writing, no upsell.</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 50rem; margin: 1rem auto;">
        We&rsquo;ll confirm your AS 4505 wind class against your block
        (engineer's report on a new build, or our own assessment on an
        existing home) and quote both sectional and roller options where both
        are viable. Honest comparison, not a single-product pitch.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content: center;">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Request a wind-class quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
